Define Data Description and Plot function¶

In [2]:
# Read data_description into a content list

with open('data_description.txt','r') as file:
    content = file.readlines()
    for line in content:
        line.rstrip('\n')
content.insert(-1,':')

#Create a funtion to extract numerical variable information from content file and plot using distplot & regplot

def info_num(data_list,x2,data,y):
    for a in range(len(data_list)):
        if (x2+':') in data_list[a]:
            for b in range(a+1,len(data_list)):
                if ':' in data_list[b]:
                    for c in range(a,b):
                        print(data_list[c])

                    f = plt.figure(figsize=((12 + (b-a)/7),4.5))
                    plt.style.use('fivethirtyeight')
                    ax1 = f.add_subplot(121)
                    ax2 = f.add_subplot(122)
                    sns.distplot(data[x2],color = 'r',ax=ax1)
                    sns.regplot(data[x2],data[y],ax=ax2)
                    plt.tight_layout()
                    plt.show()

                    print('------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------')
                    break

From Information in Data Description, we know that ['MSSubClass', 'MoSold','YrSold'] are Categorical variables
However, they show up here as Numerical Variables.
So, I converted them to String type

Categorical variables¶

I further divided Categorical Variables into Ordered and Non-Ordered features

Features which have Ranks or Sequential values are Ordered and rest are Non-ordered

I noticed that SalePrice feature has a positive skewness(right skewed).
Since linear regression models usually perform better on normally distributed data,I transformed this distribution to a normal one.
I did this by taking the log of the data

In [19]:
df['SalePrice'] = np.log1p(df['SalePrice'])
print(df['SalePrice'].describe())

sns.set(font_scale=1.25)

In [22]:
sk = []
for a in num_var:
    b = df[a].skew()
    sk.append(b)

Skewness = pd.DataFrame({'features':num_var,'skewness':sk})
Skewness = Skewness.round(2)
Skewness.sort_values(by='skewness',ascending=False,inplace=True)
f, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,12))
sns.barplot(x="skewness", y="features", data=Skewness,color = [0,114/255,178/255],ax=ax1)

# Add some data labels
y = Skewness['skewness'].tolist()

for i, v in enumerate(y):
    if v > 0:
        ax1.text(v+0.1, i+0.05, str(v), color=[213/255,94/255,0],fontsize= 12,fontweight='bold')
    else:
        ax1.text(v-1.1, i+0.05, str(v), color=[213/255,94/255,0],fontsize= 12,fontweight='bold')
In [23]:
from scipy.special import boxcox1p
#Skewness = Skewness[Skewness['features']!='LotFrontage']
Skewness = Skewness[abs(Skewness['skewness']) > 0.75]

skewed_features = Skewness['features'].tolist()
print("There are {} highly skewed numerical features".format(len(skewed_features)))

for feature in skewed_features:
    lamda = 0.15
    df[feature] = boxcox1p(df[feature], lamda)
    df[feature] += 1

There are 22 highly skewed numerical features

22 of 34 variables were highly skewed. So I normalized them using the Box-Cox Normalization
